<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-066-442  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 066 442.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  Feb 1990 v3 n2 p40(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>This is history? (Where in Time is Carmen Sandiego? computer game)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ellison, Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>This Is History? Carmen Sandiego, popular star of her own PC geography gameseries, is back in a game designed to teach history.andP;  But in reducing historyto a series of facts, a technique that worked so well in the other games,Where in Time Is Carmen Sandiego? fails to provide historical context and asense of the influence one event has on another.andM;The plot is unchanged.andP;  The Acme Detective Agency assigns you a case (theft)and a few hours in Acme's time machine to solve it.andP;  At every stop, youcollect clues to the thief's identity and whereabouts.andM;As a PC game, Where in Time is a delight: a lively mystery played out inbeautiful, high-resolution graphics of Pisa's Leaning Tower, Moscow's RedSquare, and Beijing's Forbidden City.andM;As a promoter of reference skills, it can't be beat; success comes to thosewho look things up in the New American Desk Encyclopedia, which comes withthe program.andM;But as a teacher, it disappoints.andP;  When the clue is &quot;She was going to anembassy in the Far East with General George Marshall&quot; and the travel optonsare China, Holland, Italy, and Russia, no one need understand Marshall's rolein World War II.andM;Then again, by treating history as a collection of facts to be memorizedrather than human drama to be understood and appreciated, Where in Time failsin the same way many school classes do.andP;  But it is more fun.andM;The game costs $44.95.andP;  You can reach Broderbund Software, in San Rafael,California, at 800-521-6263.andO;</TEXT></DOC>